00:30:56.890 --> 00:31:29.450
&gt;&gt; Now I mentioned at the
beginning of our program

00:31:29.450 --> 00:31:46.350
that we were going to hear from
a senator and from an author

00:31:46.350 --> 00:32:05.380
and from an illustrator, and
then I said a descendent.

00:32:05.380 --> 00:32:12.360
Can one of you raise your hand

00:32:12.360 --> 00:32:22.810
and tell me what
a descendant is?

00:32:22.810 --> 00:32:24.520
Yeah?

00:32:24.520 --> 00:32:36.850
&gt;&gt; A person from a family.

00:32:36.850 --> 00:32:39.700
&gt;&gt; A person from a family.

00:32:39.700 --> 00:32:41.000
[ Inaudible Speaker ]

00:32:41.000 --> 00:32:42.740
&gt;&gt; Say that one more time.

00:32:42.740 --> 00:32:44.040
[ Inaudible Speaker ]

00:32:44.040 --> 00:32:54.100
&gt;&gt; Yeah. So when we talk about
someone being a descendent,

00:32:54.100 --> 00:32:59.010
we're talking about
someone being descended

00:32:59.010 --> 00:33:03.060
from their ancestors, and
that's exactly why when I said

00:33:03.060 --> 00:33:05.440
that we were going to have a
descendent of Harriet Tubman

00:33:05.440 --> 00:33:09.170
with us, that's exactly
who Ms. Wyatt is.

00:33:09.170 --> 00:33:10.470
All right.

00:33:10.470 --> 00:33:11.820
I'm going to let you -- Tina,
you get started talking,

00:33:11.820 --> 00:33:13.120
and if you want me
to sit with you

00:33:13.120 --> 00:33:14.550
and ask questions,
I can do that, too.

00:33:14.550 --> 00:33:16.890
&gt;&gt; I'll just start.

00:33:16.890 --> 00:33:24.770
Thank you for coming, and
thank you for having me here.

00:33:24.770 --> 00:33:30.110
You know, when I look around
and I see all these children

00:33:30.110 --> 00:33:34.670
and I think about Aunt
Harriet and who she was

00:33:34.670 --> 00:33:40.190
and what she did, the biggest
thing that I can tell you

00:33:40.190 --> 00:33:46.010
that is relevant to everyone
is that she was just like you

00:33:46.010 --> 00:33:47.900
and she was just like me.

00:33:47.900 --> 00:33:50.700
She had hardships,
she had trials;

00:33:50.700 --> 00:33:53.300
not just slavery,
but even after.

00:33:53.300 --> 00:33:58.450
She had many obstacles
she had to overcome.

00:33:58.450 --> 00:34:04.660
And while doing that,
she had fear one time.

00:34:04.660 --> 00:34:06.970
And that was when
she first escaped

00:34:06.970 --> 00:34:11.750
at the age of 27 in 1849.

00:34:11.750 --> 00:34:15.410
She and her brothers set
out -- two of them --

00:34:15.410 --> 00:34:19.960
to escape, and they stayed out
for about two or three weeks

00:34:19.960 --> 00:34:22.200
and then they returned
because --

00:34:22.200 --> 00:34:23.610
mostly because of the fear

00:34:23.610 --> 00:34:26.650
of her brothers and
not her as much.

00:34:26.650 --> 00:34:30.790
But as soon as they got
back, she set out again.

00:34:30.790 --> 00:34:36.330
And the reason why she set out
again is because when she was

00:34:36.330 --> 00:34:44.700
around 12 years old, an overseer
from another plantation was

00:34:44.700 --> 00:34:50.200
after another enslaved person
and wanted her to stop them

00:34:50.200 --> 00:34:52.340
when she came into the store.

00:34:52.340 --> 00:34:54.100
And she wouldn't, but
she got in the way.

00:34:54.100 --> 00:34:57.480
And he threw a 2-pound
weight, iron weight,

00:34:57.480 --> 00:35:00.650
and hit her in the head.

00:35:00.650 --> 00:35:07.360
So it fractured or broke her
skull, and it drove in the cloth

00:35:07.360 --> 00:35:10.270
that she had around her
head into her skull.

00:35:10.270 --> 00:35:14.470
After that, she had
seizures, or what --

00:35:14.470 --> 00:35:16.950
you know, sleeping sickness.

00:35:16.950 --> 00:35:21.290
And that would happen
anytime, anywhere.

00:35:21.290 --> 00:35:26.070
But it was during that
time that God spoke

00:35:26.070 --> 00:35:28.540
to her, showed her visions.

00:35:28.540 --> 00:35:31.860
Now we all have a
purpose in life.

00:35:31.860 --> 00:35:33.800
God brings us here for a reason.

00:35:33.800 --> 00:35:37.740
It might be something that we
have to do that's very small,

00:35:37.740 --> 00:35:42.030
or it might be something that's
very large, but it all has

00:35:42.030 --> 00:35:43.360
to do with each other.

00:35:43.360 --> 00:35:52.040
And so when she started having
those visions, she said, not me,

00:35:52.040 --> 00:35:54.670
not me, you know, I
don't want to do this.

00:35:54.670 --> 00:35:59.200
And so He said, no, I want you
Harriet, I want you to do this.

00:35:59.200 --> 00:36:02.240
So she said OK and she
was obedient and she acted

00:36:02.240 --> 00:36:07.520
and she went and she did
what He instructed her to do.

00:36:07.520 --> 00:36:12.860
So she never did this, never
made a move without Him,

00:36:12.860 --> 00:36:17.220
without the instructions
and guidance of the Spirit.

00:36:17.220 --> 00:36:20.320
So when she did all
the things that she did

00:36:20.320 --> 00:36:30.960
from the time she left and came
back 13 times into the land

00:36:30.960 --> 00:36:38.250
where she could be enslaved
again to get her family,

00:36:38.250 --> 00:36:46.200
to get her friends, you
know, she didn't stop there.

00:36:46.200 --> 00:36:47.520
She continued on.

00:36:47.520 --> 00:36:50.140
And the reason why -- and
this is what I really want

00:36:50.140 --> 00:36:57.680
to impress upon you children
-- is that it's about love,

00:36:57.680 --> 00:37:02.160
and she embodied that love.

00:37:02.160 --> 00:37:07.700
She embodied that
selflessness and what the word

00:37:07.700 --> 00:37:10.480
of God says, love your neighbor.

00:37:10.480 --> 00:37:13.820
And that is exactly what
she did throughout her life,

00:37:13.820 --> 00:37:16.720
sometimes to her own detriment

00:37:16.720 --> 00:37:19.830
to where people would
take advantage of her.

00:37:19.830 --> 00:37:26.780
But she went on -- everywhere
she went, she was home;

00:37:26.780 --> 00:37:31.760
everywhere she went, she made a
home for those who had no home;

00:37:31.760 --> 00:37:35.860
for people who had no family,
she became their family.

00:37:35.860 --> 00:37:40.590
And she would take her own
money and she would see

00:37:40.590 --> 00:37:43.810
to whatever need they had.

00:37:43.810 --> 00:37:49.110
When she came here to
Washington from getting orders

00:37:49.110 --> 00:37:53.080
to be commissioned
in the military --

00:37:53.080 --> 00:37:54.400
and she was commissioned.

00:37:54.400 --> 00:37:55.840
It is documented.

00:37:55.840 --> 00:38:01.010
She was commissioned to be
in the military and serve

00:38:01.010 --> 00:38:05.440
in the Civil War, as
James and Lee had told you

00:38:05.440 --> 00:38:10.150
about as a scout,
a spy, a nurse.

00:38:10.150 --> 00:38:13.790
But she was the first
woman, black or white,

00:38:13.790 --> 00:38:19.170
to lead a military raid, and
she did it on the Combahee River

00:38:19.170 --> 00:38:27.890
in South Carolina where she
brought up over 700 slaves.

00:38:27.890 --> 00:38:29.960
She freed them.

00:38:29.960 --> 00:38:33.840
And then after that --
see, the job wasn't done.

00:38:33.840 --> 00:38:36.610
For her, the job was not done.

00:38:36.610 --> 00:38:40.760
Because what are they
going to do after that?

00:38:40.760 --> 00:38:43.000
How will they earn a living?

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:45.640
How will they take
care of themselves?

00:38:45.640 --> 00:38:50.290
So what she did was she took her
own money, $200 that she had --

00:38:50.290 --> 00:38:56.210
all that she had -- and
set up a wash house.

00:38:56.210 --> 00:38:57.690
She set up a kitchen.

00:38:57.690 --> 00:39:04.580
And she taught them, you
have skills; you have skills,

00:39:04.580 --> 00:39:11.180
and you have a passion;
use it to earn a living.

00:39:11.180 --> 00:39:16.000
She showed them how to market
those things that they did,

00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:21.150
who to give it to,
who to sell it to.

00:39:21.150 --> 00:39:23.890
She did all of that.

00:39:23.890 --> 00:39:30.790
So I want you to understand
that she had many obstacles.

00:39:30.790 --> 00:39:35.600
You know, the term
courageous, heroic,

00:39:35.600 --> 00:39:42.620
all those adjectives
are said about her.

00:39:42.620 --> 00:39:46.340
But like I said, she was
just like you and me.

00:39:46.340 --> 00:39:48.800
She had to overcome
many obstacles,

00:39:48.800 --> 00:39:51.800
and she did not let
anything stop her.

00:39:51.800 --> 00:39:54.610
She didn't let it get her down.

00:39:54.610 --> 00:39:59.290
One time she walked out into
a water that she did not know.

00:39:59.290 --> 00:40:04.800
Most of the time, she knew
the waterways because that's

00:40:04.800 --> 00:40:09.270
where she was raised
in Maryland,

00:40:09.270 --> 00:40:12.090
and she knew the
waterways and the land,

00:40:12.090 --> 00:40:14.980
and she worked alongside
her father

00:40:14.980 --> 00:40:18.010
who did -- who was a timberman.

00:40:18.010 --> 00:40:23.580
He, you know, brought down the
trees and things like that,

00:40:23.580 --> 00:40:25.160
and she was there with him.

00:40:25.160 --> 00:40:31.460
So she knew the land, and she
talked to watermen who were free

00:40:31.460 --> 00:40:34.090
that came down through Maryland.

00:40:34.090 --> 00:40:38.840
And there, she learned about
what was going on in other parts

00:40:38.840 --> 00:40:43.620
of the world other
than where she was.

00:40:43.620 --> 00:40:45.220
So she took all this in.

00:40:45.220 --> 00:40:49.500
Everything that she went through
became a lesson and a guide

00:40:49.500 --> 00:40:53.110
for her as she went on her way.

00:40:53.110 --> 00:40:59.370
But as she kept doing this and
going further and going further

00:40:59.370 --> 00:41:03.870
and going further, she
never forgot about the needs

00:41:03.870 --> 00:41:08.700
of others; that was always
first and foremost in her mind.

00:41:08.700 --> 00:41:12.490
And after the Civil War,
she went back to her home.

00:41:12.490 --> 00:41:14.720
And the one reason why --

00:41:14.720 --> 00:41:18.100
she had to make a decision
during the Civil War.

00:41:18.100 --> 00:41:20.650
She had to make a decision
during the Civil War,

00:41:20.650 --> 00:41:24.910
and that was to either stay
or go back to take care

00:41:24.910 --> 00:41:28.200
of her parents who were in need.

00:41:28.200 --> 00:41:30.600
And that's where she
fought for her pension.

00:41:30.600 --> 00:41:33.470
She did not receive her
pension until many years later,

00:41:33.470 --> 00:41:35.490
and that was as a nurse.

00:41:35.490 --> 00:41:37.850
She got it for her
husband first.

00:41:37.850 --> 00:41:42.320
But what did she do back
on her farm in Auburn?

00:41:42.320 --> 00:41:44.260
Again, the needs of others.

00:41:44.260 --> 00:41:48.170
She set up a home for the aged,
for the sick, for the indigent.

00:41:48.170 --> 00:41:52.780
It was always first and
foremost on her mind.

00:41:52.780 --> 00:41:56.960
And she did this all
through God showing her what

00:41:56.960 --> 00:41:58.320
to do, and she obeyed.

00:41:58.320 --> 00:41:59.620
Thank you.

00:41:59.620 --> 00:42:00.920
[ Applause ]

00:42:00.920 --> 00:42:12.260
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much, Tina.

00:42:12.260 --> 00:42:15.340
&gt;&gt; Mm-hmm.

00:42:15.340 --> 00:42:19.870
&gt;&gt; There are a couple
of microphones

00:42:19.870 --> 00:42:21.500
out there floating around.

00:42:21.500 --> 00:42:25.780
And I suspect that you all
might have some questions

00:42:25.780 --> 00:42:30.470
for our author, our
illustrator, and our descendent.

00:42:30.470 --> 00:42:32.480
So if you have a question,
please raise your hand

00:42:32.480 --> 00:42:34.650
and make sure that
one of my friends

00:42:34.650 --> 00:42:37.540
that has a microphone
can get to you.

00:42:37.540 --> 00:42:45.250
And you can say your name
and then you can go ahead

00:42:45.250 --> 00:42:47.390
and ask your question.

00:42:47.390 --> 00:42:50.630
Very good.

00:42:50.630 --> 00:42:54.800
&gt;&gt; Hi, I'm Daniel Shepherd
[assumed spelling].

00:42:54.800 --> 00:43:01.160
So -- OK. So Harriet
Tubman was a Christian?

00:43:01.160 --> 00:43:03.590
&gt;&gt; Yes. Yeah, absolutely,
yes, she was.

00:43:03.590 --> 00:43:05.000
Very religious.

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:06.300
&gt;&gt; Mm-hmm.

00:43:06.300 --> 00:43:07.850
&gt;&gt; Prayed throughout most
of her escapes [laughs].

00:43:07.850 --> 00:43:11.970
I think most of us would
if we were escaping.

00:43:11.970 --> 00:43:14.360
&gt;&gt; Mm-hmm.

00:43:14.360 --> 00:43:15.660
[ Inaudible Speaker ]

00:43:15.660 --> 00:43:16.960
&gt;&gt; Sure.

00:43:16.960 --> 00:43:18.260
&gt;&gt; Hi. My name is Yasneve
[phonetic] and I have

00:43:18.260 --> 00:43:20.560
to ask you a question is,

00:43:20.560 --> 00:43:27.080
how old was Harriet Tubman
when she was a nurse?

00:43:27.080 --> 00:43:29.010
&gt;&gt; How old was she?

00:43:29.010 --> 00:43:30.980
&gt;&gt; She was probably
in her 40's --

00:43:30.980 --> 00:43:32.280
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I don't know.

00:43:32.280 --> 00:43:33.580
&gt;&gt; -- around that time.

00:43:33.580 --> 00:43:37.920
&gt;&gt; They didn't have birth
certificates at that time, so --

00:43:37.920 --> 00:43:40.210
especially for slaves,
it wasn't really marked

00:43:40.210 --> 00:43:42.580
when they were born, so
it's hard to tell exactly --

00:43:42.580 --> 00:43:43.880
&gt;&gt; Mm-hmm.

00:43:43.880 --> 00:43:45.180
&gt;&gt; -- how old she was.

00:43:45.180 --> 00:43:48.180
&gt;&gt; But she was 27
when she escaped.

00:43:48.180 --> 00:43:51.690
We know that she
was born in 1822,

00:43:51.690 --> 00:43:53.890
but we don't know the date.

00:43:53.890 --> 00:43:57.430
And so it was 1849,
so you kind of got

00:43:57.430 --> 00:43:59.250
to do the math a little bit.

00:43:59.250 --> 00:44:08.790
So she was, like, in her
40's, somewhere around there.

00:44:08.790 --> 00:44:10.090
&gt;&gt; Another question?

00:44:10.090 --> 00:44:11.390
[ Inaudible Speakers ]

00:44:11.390 --> 00:44:24.490
&gt;&gt; Hello. My name is
Violet [assumed spelling].

00:44:24.490 --> 00:44:27.940
Did some white people like her?

00:44:27.940 --> 00:44:29.240
&gt;&gt; Oh, sure.

00:44:29.240 --> 00:44:30.540
&gt;&gt; Mm-hmm.

00:44:30.540 --> 00:44:31.840
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:44:31.840 --> 00:44:33.140
&gt;&gt; Mm-hmm.

00:44:33.140 --> 00:44:34.440
&gt;&gt; Do you want to say --

00:44:34.440 --> 00:44:37.190
&gt;&gt; Yes. I mean, I'm sure that
some white people liked her,

00:44:37.190 --> 00:44:41.930
but I'm also sure that some
white people didn't like her.

00:44:41.930 --> 00:44:47.740
You know, what she was doing
was essentially what --

00:44:47.740 --> 00:44:52.250
in their minds, they saw her
as stealing their property.

00:44:52.250 --> 00:44:56.290
But what they were doing was
stealing away their own freedom.

00:44:56.290 --> 00:44:58.960
So I think that there
might have been a conflict

00:44:58.960 --> 00:45:01.410
that they saw that
was happening.

00:45:01.410 --> 00:45:04.280
So, yeah, I'm sure that --

00:45:04.280 --> 00:45:07.190
but there were white people
who were also fighting

00:45:07.190 --> 00:45:08.710
for the freedom

00:45:08.710 --> 00:45:10.290
of African-Americans
and there were --

00:45:10.290 --> 00:45:11.590
&gt;&gt; In Newark.

00:45:11.590 --> 00:45:13.600
&gt;&gt; -- white soldiers
who were fighting, also.

00:45:13.600 --> 00:45:15.970
So yes, I'm sure
there were both.

00:45:15.970 --> 00:45:18.500
&gt;&gt; And, you know, a part

00:45:18.500 --> 00:45:22.170
of her network was called
the Underground Railroad.

00:45:22.170 --> 00:45:25.680
And that was a network
of people, not trains,

00:45:25.680 --> 00:45:31.000
but a network of people that
were in secret that helped her.

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:35.840
And a lot of them were
white that helped her.

00:45:35.840 --> 00:45:40.050
So you had to know where to
go, and -- and Thomas Garrett,

00:45:40.050 --> 00:45:43.350
which was really a good
friend of hers, you know,

00:45:43.350 --> 00:45:46.420
when she would come
and she'd want money.

00:45:46.420 --> 00:45:49.770
And one time he told her, he
said, well, if you're coming

00:45:49.770 --> 00:45:53.350
for somebody else, I'm not going
to give it to you, Harriet.

00:45:53.350 --> 00:45:56.490
But she told him, she said,
well, you're going to give it

00:45:56.490 --> 00:45:58.820
to me because it is
for somebody else.

00:45:58.820 --> 00:46:00.120
So, yeah.

00:46:00.120 --> 00:46:07.310
&gt;&gt; I think we have a question
on this side in purple.

00:46:07.310 --> 00:46:10.010
&gt;&gt; Hi. My name is
Mykia [phonetic].

00:46:10.010 --> 00:46:13.600
Why do you like to draw?

00:46:13.600 --> 00:46:18.840
&gt;&gt; Oh. There's something
magical about it.

00:46:18.840 --> 00:46:21.460
When I was very young, I
wanted to be a magician.

00:46:21.460 --> 00:46:24.050
But, you know, you have
a white piece of paper

00:46:24.050 --> 00:46:27.690
and you have something -- a
drawing instrument in your hand,

00:46:27.690 --> 00:46:31.150
and just by passing that drawing
instrument across the paper,

00:46:31.150 --> 00:46:36.070
you create shapes and images
that people appreciate.

00:46:36.070 --> 00:46:38.880
And that's one of the many
reasons why I love to draw

00:46:38.880 --> 00:46:41.910
because you can make
something and you can see it,

00:46:41.910 --> 00:46:45.510
what you made, almost instantly.

00:46:45.510 --> 00:46:47.430
&gt;&gt; Good question.

00:46:47.430 --> 00:46:51.520
&gt;&gt; OK. I see a couple
of hands going up.

00:46:51.520 --> 00:46:53.260
&gt;&gt; Hi. My name is Sarah
[assumed spelling].

00:46:53.260 --> 00:46:56.160
How long did it take
you guys to make a book?

00:46:56.160 --> 00:47:00.680
&gt;&gt; Well, it takes a long time
to make a book because you have

00:47:00.680 --> 00:47:03.230
to do the research, and
then you do the writing

00:47:03.230 --> 00:47:06.960
and then you revise it
and you revise it again.

00:47:06.960 --> 00:47:09.940
So generally for me,
it takes about --

00:47:09.940 --> 00:47:14.750
let's say about six
months to write the book.

00:47:14.750 --> 00:47:18.250
And then it goes off
to the illustrator,

00:47:18.250 --> 00:47:20.330
and then sometimes the
illustrator can take --

00:47:20.330 --> 00:47:21.790
&gt;&gt; Yeah. Can I say --

00:47:21.790 --> 00:47:23.090
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:47:23.090 --> 00:47:24.390
&gt;&gt; The illustrator
would take about --

00:47:24.390 --> 00:47:27.900
it takes me about a year to
illustrate a book, right?

00:47:27.900 --> 00:47:29.950
It has to come from
Lesa, it comes to me,

00:47:29.950 --> 00:47:31.250
and it takes about a year.

00:47:31.250 --> 00:47:32.670
&gt;&gt; And then it takes
about another --

00:47:32.670 --> 00:47:33.970
&gt;&gt; Year.

00:47:33.970 --> 00:47:35.270
&gt;&gt; -- year or two
to print the book.

00:47:35.270 --> 00:47:37.550
So it takes a pretty
long time to make a book.

00:47:37.550 --> 00:47:38.910
&gt;&gt; Good question.

00:47:38.910 --> 00:47:40.210
&gt;&gt; All right.

00:47:40.210 --> 00:47:41.510
Over here in the yellow.

00:47:41.510 --> 00:47:42.810
&gt;&gt; Hi. My name is Jairo
Torres [phonetic].

00:47:42.810 --> 00:47:48.170
And when she was a slave, when
she tried to escape to houses,

00:47:48.170 --> 00:47:50.350
she saw [inaudible]
to give her clues

00:47:50.350 --> 00:47:52.700
that that was a safe house.

00:47:52.700 --> 00:47:54.000
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:47:54.000 --> 00:47:55.920
A comment.

00:47:55.920 --> 00:47:58.870
&gt;&gt; OK. All right.

00:47:58.870 --> 00:48:00.170
Go ahead.

00:48:00.170 --> 00:48:02.890
&gt;&gt; I didn't understand --

00:48:02.890 --> 00:48:04.650
&gt;&gt; Hi. My name is Natasha
[assumed spelling].

00:48:04.650 --> 00:48:07.570
And when are you guys
going to make a new book?

00:48:07.570 --> 00:48:11.330
&gt;&gt; When are we going
to make a new book?

00:48:11.330 --> 00:48:12.690
We're always making new books.

00:48:12.690 --> 00:48:19.040
We have a book coming out in May
about Venus and Serena Williams.

00:48:19.040 --> 00:48:20.810
I have a novel coming out,

00:48:20.810 --> 00:48:31.060
and then we're always
working on new projects.

00:48:31.060 --> 00:48:33.690
&gt;&gt; Great question.

00:48:33.690 --> 00:48:37.860
&gt;&gt; How -- no, no, no.

00:48:37.860 --> 00:48:39.550
&gt;&gt; Are you sure?

00:48:39.550 --> 00:48:40.850
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:48:40.850 --> 00:48:42.560
&gt;&gt; It's all right.

00:48:42.560 --> 00:48:44.240
We'll come back.

00:48:44.240 --> 00:48:47.980
&gt;&gt; When Harriet Tubman slept,

00:48:47.980 --> 00:48:51.200
did they hit her instantly
when she fell asleep?

00:48:51.200 --> 00:48:52.500
&gt;&gt; When she did what?

00:48:52.500 --> 00:48:53.800
&gt;&gt; When she fell asleep.

00:48:53.800 --> 00:48:55.100
&gt;&gt; Uh-huh?

00:48:55.100 --> 00:48:56.400
&gt;&gt; Did they hit her?

00:48:56.400 --> 00:48:57.700
&gt;&gt; Did they hit her?

00:48:57.700 --> 00:48:59.000
&gt;&gt; To wake her up?

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:00.300
&gt;&gt; To wake her up?

00:49:00.300 --> 00:49:05.200
No. You know, everyone knew what
happened to her, so the people

00:49:05.200 --> 00:49:06.820
around her would always
just say, well, you know,

00:49:06.820 --> 00:49:09.540
there she is, she's
going off again.

00:49:09.540 --> 00:49:12.720
So they would wait
until she woke up.

00:49:15.720 --> 00:49:17.450
&gt;&gt; OK. Yeah.

00:49:17.450 --> 00:49:19.000
&gt;&gt; Hello, my name is
Brian [assumed spelling].

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:21.780
My question is, how did
the illustrator become a

00:49:21.780 --> 00:49:23.760
good drawer?

00:49:23.760 --> 00:49:27.050
&gt;&gt; Lots of years of practicing,
which is a lot of fun

00:49:27.050 --> 00:49:29.250
because I love drawing.

00:49:29.250 --> 00:49:32.720
So as a kid I drew a lot.

00:49:32.720 --> 00:49:34.270
High school.

00:49:34.270 --> 00:49:36.110
Then I went to college.

00:49:36.110 --> 00:49:39.070
I studied art in
college, illustration.

00:49:39.070 --> 00:49:43.070
And after I graduated, I
continued to take classes.

00:49:43.070 --> 00:49:45.710
I go to museums and
I look at art.

00:49:45.710 --> 00:49:48.400
I continue to practice and draw.

00:49:48.400 --> 00:49:50.640
If you like drawing,
it's a fun job

00:49:50.640 --> 00:49:53.340
because you're basically doing
what you love all the time.

00:49:53.340 --> 00:49:55.010
&gt;&gt; All right.

00:49:55.010 --> 00:49:56.310
&gt;&gt; Good answer.

00:49:56.310 --> 00:49:57.610
&gt;&gt; All right.

00:49:57.610 --> 00:49:59.110
I think you've -- nope,
maybe not [laughs].

00:49:59.110 --> 00:50:00.410
Yes?

00:50:00.410 --> 00:50:04.670
&gt;&gt; Hi, my name is Janet
[assumed spelling].

00:50:07.170 --> 00:50:11.060
And my question is, what
was the thing she got hit

00:50:11.060 --> 00:50:12.360
with made out of?

00:50:12.360 --> 00:50:13.660
&gt;&gt; Pardon me?

00:50:13.660 --> 00:50:15.510
&gt;&gt; The thing that --
what was it made out of?

00:50:15.510 --> 00:50:19.640
&gt;&gt; What was the thing
that she got hit out of --

00:50:19.640 --> 00:50:20.940
&gt;&gt; Oh, iron.

00:50:20.940 --> 00:50:22.240
&gt;&gt; Iron.

00:50:22.240 --> 00:50:23.540
&gt;&gt; Iron, yeah.

00:50:23.540 --> 00:50:24.840
&gt;&gt; Very heavy.

00:50:24.840 --> 00:50:26.140
&gt;&gt; It was quite a blow, also.

00:50:26.140 --> 00:50:31.530
It really did change her
life, that blow to the head.

00:50:31.530 --> 00:50:32.830
&gt;&gt; Mm-hmm.

00:50:32.830 --> 00:50:34.130
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:50:34.130 --> 00:50:36.090
&gt;&gt; My name is Fabiola
[phonetic], and I want to know

00:50:36.090 --> 00:50:39.540
who in your family
supported you in illustrating?

00:50:39.540 --> 00:50:40.840
[ Laughter ]

00:50:40.840 --> 00:50:44.380
&gt;&gt; Actually, my --
I grew up with my --

00:50:44.380 --> 00:50:48.750
I lived with my grandmother
for about 16 years,

00:50:48.750 --> 00:50:50.280
and she really supported my art.

00:50:50.280 --> 00:50:52.060
She always bought me supplies,

00:50:52.060 --> 00:50:53.830
allowed me to buy
different supplies,

00:50:53.830 --> 00:50:57.360
and she was my biggest
supporter.

00:50:57.360 --> 00:50:58.660
&gt;&gt; Good question.

00:50:58.660 --> 00:50:59.960
All right.

00:50:59.960 --> 00:51:02.520
Yeah, go ahead.

00:51:02.520 --> 00:51:04.940
&gt;&gt; My name is Samaya
[phonetic], and I want to know,

00:51:04.940 --> 00:51:07.260
if Harriet Tubman
was alive today,

00:51:07.260 --> 00:51:09.740
what advice would she give us?

00:51:09.740 --> 00:51:11.040
&gt;&gt; Oh.

00:51:11.040 --> 00:51:12.340
[ Chuckling ]

00:51:12.340 --> 00:51:13.640
&gt;&gt; Nice.

00:51:13.640 --> 00:51:14.940
[ Applause ]

00:51:14.940 --> 00:51:16.240
&gt;&gt; Careful now.

00:51:16.240 --> 00:51:17.540
Be careful.

00:51:17.540 --> 00:51:18.840
[ Laughter ]

00:51:18.840 --> 00:51:20.140
&gt;&gt; Well, what I think she
would do is tell you to --

00:51:20.140 --> 00:51:21.440
&gt;&gt; Do well in school.

00:51:21.440 --> 00:51:22.740
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:51:22.740 --> 00:51:25.670
&gt;&gt; I believe education
would probably be --

00:51:25.670 --> 00:51:26.970
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:51:26.970 --> 00:51:28.270
&gt;&gt; -- a very important thing.

00:51:28.270 --> 00:51:29.570
&gt;&gt; Yeah, because it was
taken away from her.

00:51:29.570 --> 00:51:30.870
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:51:30.870 --> 00:51:32.170
&gt;&gt; She couldn't read,
she couldn't write.

00:51:32.170 --> 00:51:33.470
&gt;&gt; Mm-hmm.

00:51:33.470 --> 00:51:34.770
&gt;&gt; But I think she would
also tell you to stand

00:51:34.770 --> 00:51:36.830
up for what you believe
and to love others

00:51:36.830 --> 00:51:40.890
because that's what she did.

00:51:40.890 --> 00:51:42.190
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:51:42.190 --> 00:51:43.490
&gt;&gt; Great questions.

00:51:43.490 --> 00:51:44.880
&gt;&gt; You know, a lot of things --
you know, one other thing I want

00:51:44.880 --> 00:51:47.790
to say is that because
there's a lot of bullying going

00:51:47.790 --> 00:51:51.470
on in schools today, and,
you know, of people saying,

00:51:51.470 --> 00:51:52.970
I don't like you,
I don't like you,

00:51:52.970 --> 00:51:55.650
and trying to get
other people not

00:51:55.650 --> 00:51:58.730
to associate with other people.

00:51:58.730 --> 00:52:03.300
You know, she would
tell you to not do that.

00:52:03.300 --> 00:52:06.030
You know, to find something --
because there's always something

00:52:06.030 --> 00:52:09.480
in everyone that you can find
-- you know, that you can like.

00:52:09.480 --> 00:52:10.780
&gt;&gt; Mm-hmm, all.

00:52:10.780 --> 00:52:12.080
&gt;&gt; Yeah, and that
there's something

00:52:12.080 --> 00:52:14.740
that you can connect with.

00:52:14.740 --> 00:52:16.060
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:52:16.060 --> 00:52:18.630
&gt;&gt; OK. One more question,
I think.

00:52:18.630 --> 00:52:21.090
&gt;&gt; Hi, my name is Dillon
[assumed spelling].

00:52:21.090 --> 00:52:24.820
When did you guys
publish your first book?

00:52:24.820 --> 00:52:31.330
&gt;&gt; My first book was published
in 1990, a long time ago.

00:52:31.330 --> 00:52:32.710
And your book was --

00:52:32.710 --> 00:52:35.770
&gt;&gt; Yeah. Our first book
together was published in 2000.

00:52:35.770 --> 00:52:37.070
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:52:37.070 --> 00:52:38.370
&gt;&gt; Very nice.

00:52:38.370 --> 00:52:39.670
&gt;&gt; Very good.

00:52:39.670 --> 00:52:40.970
Good, guys.

00:52:40.970 --> 00:52:42.270
[ Applause ]

00:52:42.270 --> 00:52:48.930
So I want to thank you
all for your questions.

00:52:48.930 --> 00:52:52.840
I also want to thank
you for your listening

00:52:52.840 --> 00:52:54.140
because I was really good.

00:52:54.140 --> 00:52:57.110
It's hard to sit still for
this long and be as attentive

00:52:57.110 --> 00:52:59.270
as you all have been,
so thank you for that.

00:52:59.270 --> 00:53:02.440
I want to show you
two little pictures

00:53:02.440 --> 00:53:04.640
up on these screens here.

00:53:04.640 --> 00:53:07.920
When Senator Van Hollen was
talking with you, he mentioned

00:53:07.920 --> 00:53:11.320
that the Library of Congress
and the national Museum

00:53:11.320 --> 00:53:12.680
of African American History

00:53:12.680 --> 00:53:15.010
and Culture had recently
worked together

00:53:15.010 --> 00:53:16.770
to acquire a new scrapbook

00:53:16.770 --> 00:53:21.920
that includes a previously
before not seen image

00:53:21.920 --> 00:53:23.220
of Harriet Tubman.

00:53:23.220 --> 00:53:24.590
And you guys are each
going to get a copy

00:53:24.590 --> 00:53:26.990
of that photograph today, but
you're also going to get a copy

00:53:26.990 --> 00:53:29.270
of a photograph that
we've seen before.

00:53:29.270 --> 00:53:30.570
How many of you have
seen this photograph

00:53:30.570 --> 00:53:31.990
of Harriet Tubman before?

00:53:31.990 --> 00:53:33.810
Yeah, it's kind of
a famous photograph.

00:53:33.810 --> 00:53:36.760
And it really reflects
Harriet Tubman

00:53:36.760 --> 00:53:39.860
at the later part of her life.

00:53:39.860 --> 00:53:42.610
And the new photograph
of Harriet Tubman --

00:53:42.610 --> 00:53:43.910
&gt;&gt; What?

00:53:43.910 --> 00:53:45.210
&gt;&gt; It says right
there Nurse Tubman.

00:53:45.210 --> 00:53:46.510
&gt;&gt; -- is this one.

00:53:46.510 --> 00:53:47.810
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:53:47.810 --> 00:53:50.830
&gt;&gt; And you can see that it's
significantly years prior

00:53:50.830 --> 00:53:52.750
to the one we just saw.

00:53:52.750 --> 00:53:59.660
This is the new image that
we believe was taken in 1868

00:53:59.660 --> 00:54:03.220
of her, so we have a sense
of what she might have looked

00:54:03.220 --> 00:54:06.850
like when she was
in her late 40's.

00:54:06.850 --> 00:54:09.230
Remember at the beginning
of this talk

00:54:09.230 --> 00:54:12.320
when I mentioned how we
could describe people

00:54:12.320 --> 00:54:15.140
like Thomas Jefferson and
James Madison and John Adams

00:54:15.140 --> 00:54:18.680
in all those ways, and I
introduced Senator Van Hollen,

00:54:18.680 --> 00:54:21.430
and I described him as
many different things

00:54:21.430 --> 00:54:24.200
in addition to being a senator?

00:54:24.200 --> 00:54:26.780
In the story that the
Ransomes read to us,

00:54:26.780 --> 00:54:28.730
we learned a little bit
about Harriet Tubman

00:54:28.730 --> 00:54:30.560
and the various roles
that she played.

00:54:30.560 --> 00:54:33.890
Can one of you raise your
hand and tell me one thing

00:54:33.890 --> 00:54:36.210
that Harriet Tubman was?

00:54:36.210 --> 00:54:38.420
What was one thing that -- yeah?

00:54:38.420 --> 00:54:40.250
What was she?

00:54:40.250 --> 00:54:41.550
&gt;&gt; Moses.

00:54:41.550 --> 00:54:42.850
&gt;&gt; She was Moses.

00:54:42.850 --> 00:54:44.150
Excellent, yeah.

00:54:44.150 --> 00:54:45.490
She was a conductor on
the Underground Railroad

00:54:45.490 --> 00:54:46.940
and referred to as Moses.

00:54:46.940 --> 00:54:48.240
That was awesome.

00:54:48.240 --> 00:54:49.540
What else was she?

00:54:49.540 --> 00:54:50.840
Yeah, in the yellow.

00:54:50.840 --> 00:54:52.140
[ Inaudible Speaker ]

00:54:52.140 --> 00:54:55.390
&gt;&gt; I can't hear you.

00:54:55.390 --> 00:54:56.690
Sorry.

00:54:56.690 --> 00:54:58.250
&gt;&gt; She was a fugitive.

00:54:58.250 --> 00:54:59.840
She was a fugitive.

00:54:59.840 --> 00:55:01.790
&gt;&gt; I still didn't hear you.

00:55:01.790 --> 00:55:03.090
I'm sorry.

00:55:03.090 --> 00:55:04.390
&gt;&gt; A fugitive.

00:55:04.390 --> 00:55:05.690
&gt;&gt; Oh, she was a fugitive, yeah.

00:55:05.690 --> 00:55:06.990
Yes, she was.

00:55:06.990 --> 00:55:08.290
OK, what else was she?

00:55:08.290 --> 00:55:09.590
In the purple.

00:55:09.590 --> 00:55:10.890
&gt;&gt; She was a nurse.

00:55:10.890 --> 00:55:12.190
&gt;&gt; She was a nurse, excellent.

00:55:12.190 --> 00:55:13.490
And right here in the
middle, what was she?

00:55:13.490 --> 00:55:14.790
&gt;&gt; A spy.

00:55:14.790 --> 00:55:16.090
&gt;&gt; She was a spy, yeah.

00:55:16.090 --> 00:55:17.390
I heard him, yep.

00:55:17.390 --> 00:55:20.210
Yeah. So she was a nurse,
she was a spy, she was Moses.

00:55:20.210 --> 00:55:21.510
Anything else?

00:55:21.510 --> 00:55:22.810
&gt;&gt; A nurse!

00:55:22.810 --> 00:55:24.110
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:55:24.110 --> 00:55:25.830
&gt;&gt; She was a slave.

00:55:25.830 --> 00:55:29.600
&gt;&gt; She was enslaved early in
her life, but what else was she?

00:55:29.600 --> 00:55:30.900
&gt;&gt; She was a scout.

00:55:30.900 --> 00:55:32.200
&gt;&gt; She was a scout.

00:55:32.200 --> 00:55:33.500
You guys are good.

00:55:33.500 --> 00:55:35.250
Yeah. So Harriet Tubman
was lots of things.

00:55:35.250 --> 00:55:40.050
And just to repeat, the images
that you have give us a glimpse

00:55:40.050 --> 00:55:43.340
of what she looked like at
different stages in her life.

00:55:43.340 --> 00:55:46.110
And the book that you
are all receiving a copy

00:55:46.110 --> 00:55:50.950
of is the Ransomes' book
about before she was Harriet.

00:55:50.950 --> 00:55:53.140
And I hope that you
keep in mind that --

00:55:53.140 --> 00:55:56.410
like, right now you guys are all
students, but I know that some

00:55:56.410 --> 00:56:00.300
of you are athletes and some
of you already are artists.

00:56:00.300 --> 00:56:03.290
And I know that some of you
like to cook, so you must be,

00:56:03.290 --> 00:56:05.090
like, brilliant chefs.

00:56:05.090 --> 00:56:06.850
But you are a lot of things.

00:56:06.850 --> 00:56:09.690
And you are also all of the
things that you're going

00:56:09.690 --> 00:56:12.780
to become, and that's
exciting to think about.

00:56:12.780 --> 00:56:14.080
It's exciting to think

00:56:14.080 --> 00:56:16.560
about welcoming you all back
here someday to talk to us

00:56:16.560 --> 00:56:18.960
about the books that
you've written or the books

00:56:18.960 --> 00:56:20.450
that you've illustrated.

00:56:20.450 --> 00:56:23.900
So thank you for coming to
the Library of Congress today.

00:56:23.900 --> 00:56:28.170
Thank you very much for
your attentiveness --

00:56:28.170 --> 00:56:29.470
[ Applause ]

00:56:29.470 --> 00:56:30.770
-- and your questions.

00:56:30.770 --> 00:56:32.070
[ Applause ]

